pr_body:
- Refactored code to make it more testable.
- Added titles into the UI to make it more clear which is the local note that'll be saved.
- Titles of the notes themselves are also shown now.

### Questions
I was reading an article on how to make my code testable, and it suggested that I should make my external used classes passed into the constructor like this: https://github.com/joplin/plugin-conflict-resolution/blob/week2/src/DiffWindow.ts#L6-L16
I think the idea is that I'd be able to pass mock objects into the class whilst testing instead of the real deal.

Is this approach correct, IDK why I feel like I'm doing something wrong as I still do import the classes above haha ?

pr_title: Made the UI responsive to UI changes.
pr_body:

pr_title: Fix setFitToContent error in old Joplin.
pr_body:
I've made a sort of failsafe where it simply reverts the CSS changes back to fixed px values in case setFitToContent doesn't exist. That way the plugin still works with old Joplin versions.

I could have just dropped support for older versions and waited a new Joplin release, but didn't wanna do that.

pr_title: Desktop: Added enabled check before adding to NoteListContextMenu list.
pr_body:
The `enabledCondition` was simply ignored completely when adding buttons to the NoteListContextMenu. I've added the needed condition to only append commands that are enabled according to commandService's `isEnabled`.

I noticed that the code in NoteListUtils apprently is outdated ? Like it doesn't use any of the CommandService stuff about comnmandEnabled and when clauses but simply does the checks manually. I focused my changes on the plugins part and left the others.

I've tested this in my own plugin via having a command that only works with `inConflictFolder` and the button indeed now only shows for notes inside the Conflict Folder. Not the outside.  I'm not sure if unit tests are needed for this change.

pr_title: Desktop: Resolves #5288: Added back fitContent without breaking panels.
pr_body:
I've realized my issue. I assumed that UserWebview was only used by dialogs which was fatal haha. Even when testing I only tested plugins that had dialogs in them and completely forgot that there's other UI elements that shared the same Webview file.

The issue was that `vw` and `vh` are relative to the browser dimensions and not it's parents. This is perfectly fine for dialogs as they're indeed relative to the window but when it comes to panels, those MUST be sized relative to their parent or else they'd have really large dimensions as we saw in Note Tabs plugins.

So a possible fix would be to simply apply the `vw` and `vh` stuff ONLY for dialogs but the rest of UI must still use `100%`. This was achieved by simply moving over the code to `UserWebviewDialog` instead of `UserWebview`

### Testing
I've tested Note Tabs plugin panels, Tagging plugin dialog (uses fitToContent), Conflict Resolution dialog (doesn't use fit to content), and finally the outline plugin.  All of them seemed to work perfectly now :)

When `fitToContent` is true, it'll be sized according to the content thus having exact pixel values. When it's false, it'll have 100% width and 100% height, filling it's parent completely.

We want this to be false so that the Webview grows to fill to the parent Dialog div.

## Dialog
When `fitToContent` is true, we'll leave the dimensions for this as `auto` in order to make it grow with the Webview. If it's false, we want to make this Dialog `90vw` wide `80vh` high. Ofcourse the Webview will always fill this 100%.

I did think about having the Dialog always at 90vh and 80vh but this caused issues like this:

pr_body:
- Refactored code to make it more testable.
- Added titles into the UI to make it more clear which is the local note that'll be saved.
- Titles of the notes themselves are also shown now.

### Questions
I was reading an article on how to make my code testable, and it suggested that I should make my external used classes passed into the constructor like this: https://github.com/joplin/plugin-conflict-resolution/blob/week2/src/DiffWindow.ts#L6-L16
I think the idea is that I'd be able to pass mock objects into the class whilst testing instead of the real deal.

Is this approach correct, IDK why I feel like I'm doing something wrong as I still do import the classes above haha ?

pr_title: Desktop: Resolves #5288: Added back fitContent without breaking panels.
pr_body:
I've realized my issue. I assumed that UserWebview was only used by dialogs which was fatal haha. Even when testing I only tested plugins that had dialogs in them and completely forgot that there's other UI elements that shared the same Webview file.

The issue was that `vw` and `vh` are relative to the browser dimensions and not it's parents. This is perfectly fine for dialogs as they're indeed relative to the window but when it comes to panels, those MUST be sized relative to their parent or else they'd have really large dimensions as we saw in Note Tabs plugins.

So a possible fix would be to simply apply the `vw` and `vh` stuff ONLY for dialogs but the rest of UI must still use `100%`. This was achieved by simply moving over the code to `UserWebviewDialog` instead of `UserWebview`

### Testing
I've tested Note Tabs plugin panels, Tagging plugin dialog (uses fitToContent), Conflict Resolution dialog (doesn't use fit to content), and finally the outline plugin.  All of them seemed to work perfectly now :)
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 688108993, 'comment_body': 'Since you now moved the prop to the Dialog component, do we still need it here?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 12, 21, 50, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'laurent22', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 688109990, 'comment_body': 'Yes because I still want the Userwebview to have 100% width and 100% height.  (Like panels)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 12, 21, 53, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Ahmad45123', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 688356835, 'comment_body': "Something's not right with having this property on two nested components. Could you explain how it work when fitToContent is true, and when it's false? What's the dimensions of Dialog, and what's the dimensions of UserWebview?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 13, 8, 56, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'laurent22', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 688671290, 'comment_body': "## UserWebview

When `fitToContent` is true, it'll be sized according to the content thus having exact pixel values. When it's false, it'll have 100% width and 100% height, filling it's parent completely.

We want this to be false so that the Webview grows to fill to the parent Dialog div.

## Dialog
When `fitToContent` is true, we'll leave the dimensions for this as `auto` in order to make it grow with the Webview. If it's false, we want to make this Dialog `90vw` wide `80vh` high. Ofcourse the Webview will always fill this 100%.

I did think about having the Dialog always at 90vh and 80vh but this caused issues like this: 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8184424/129396905-60421538-55e7-4aa5-ab80-2ff44e59394f.png)

The `iframe` has exact pixel dimensions but the Dialog div is way larger. _(it must be auto when fitToContent is on.)_", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 13, 17, 26, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Ahmad45123', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 688685527, 'comment_body': 'So do you see the problem, and do you have any suggestion on how to fix it?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 13, 17, 51, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'laurent22', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 688686069, 'comment_body': "I'm not sure where is the problem no?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 13, 17, 52, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Ahmad45123', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 688687166, 'comment_body': "In short, To achieve full screen idea, we want the Dialog to have `90vw and 80vh` and the Webview must have 100% dimensions in order to fill this Dialog parent. Maybe there's a better way then what I did ?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 13, 17, 54, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Ahmad45123', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 691135633, 'comment_body': "I couldn't quite see from the diff but your change makes sense actually. Thanks for clarifying, and let's merge then.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 18, 11, 9, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'laurent22', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Desktop: Added enabled check before adding to NoteListContextMenu list.
pr_body:
The `enabledCondition` was simply ignored completely when adding buttons to the NoteListContextMenu. I've added the needed condition to only append commands that are enabled according to commandService's `isEnabled`.

I noticed that the code in NoteListUtils apprently is outdated ? Like it doesn't use any of the CommandService stuff about comnmandEnabled and when clauses but simply does the checks manually. I focused my changes on the plugins part and left the others.

I've tested this in my own plugin via having a command that only works with `inConflictFolder` and the button indeed now only shows for notes inside the Conflict Folder. Not the outside.  I'm not sure if unit tests are needed for this change.
pr_review_comments: [{'comment_id': 684806249, 'comment_body': 'Just call `cmdService.isEnabled` directly, no need to create a helper function that does nothing for this.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 8, 17, 35, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'laurent22', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 684806322, 'comment_body': 'remove', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 8, 17, 35, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'laurent22', 'type': 'User'}]
